1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:17,720
It's great to be with you again this morning. Let me commend you. Some churches don't know how to worship when the pastor's gone, and when you take away the whole pastoral staff, things just fall apart, and God's been the focus this morning, and that's the way it should be all the time, and I'm grateful to be with you.

2
00:00:17,720 --> 00:00:22,860
I am the executive director at Thousand Pines Christian Camp and Conference Center, your

3
00:00:22,860 --> 00:00:30,650
American Baptist camp up in Crestline, California, and I'm just thrilled to be with you.

4
00:00:31,310 --> 00:00:35,570
I have a little bit of PR work to do, but not too much.

5
00:00:35,670 --> 00:00:38,190
I want to focus on the word today.

6
00:00:38,730 --> 00:00:42,310
We have board members in your church that I am grateful for.

7
00:00:42,410 --> 00:00:46,970
Bruce Steele, Ron Stevens, Dave Estridge are all members of the Thousand Pines board.

8
00:00:46,970 --> 00:00:49,830
George Mattis was a member of the Thousand Pines board,

9
00:00:49,890 --> 00:00:53,210
and we now claim him as our missionary to Europe.

10
00:00:53,350 --> 00:00:55,390
I mean, I know you do as well, but that's okay.

11
00:00:55,450 --> 00:00:56,150
We'll share him.

12
00:00:56,930 --> 00:01:01,310
And I know the Fullerton youth will be at Thousand Pines next week,

13
00:01:01,330 --> 00:01:04,250
so I hope that you'll be praying for them all week

14
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:06,690
because it isn't just what we do on the mountaintop

15
00:01:06,690 --> 00:01:08,710
that makes a difference in their lives.

16
00:01:08,830 --> 00:01:11,810
It's the sense of expectation that they bring with them

17
00:01:11,810 --> 00:01:15,610
and the sense of expectation that leads you to the throne of grace

18
00:01:15,610 --> 00:01:21,150
to pray for them that changes lives a thousand pines, and that's what we're all about.

19
00:01:21,950 --> 00:01:26,570
In your bulletin, I believe you got an insert this morning. It's about a great special event

20
00:01:26,570 --> 00:01:32,090
that we have happening in your backyard. I'm going to take First Baptist Fullerton attendance

21
00:01:32,090 --> 00:01:38,510
on that day to see how many of you are with us. I want to tell you quite frankly that in this year,

22
00:01:39,250 --> 00:01:45,430
and I'm with GW, I'm sorry, our president. I'm with the president. The economy is going to

23
00:01:45,430 --> 00:01:53,280
turn around this year. But without this event last year, we would not only be in the situation

24
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:58,920
at Thousand Pines where I have had to clean a few restrooms and wash a few dishes recently,

25
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:05,550
but we would have had young people not be able to go to camp because we wouldn't have had

26
00:02:05,550 --> 00:02:12,290
scholarship funds for them. And yet last year, God gave us a great event, a lot of money was raised,

27
00:02:12,290 --> 00:02:16,650
and virtually every dime we raised was used for scholarships.

28
00:02:17,110 --> 00:02:20,530
We expect the same to be true even in an improving economy

29
00:02:20,530 --> 00:02:24,890
and we hope that you'll support this worthy cause when you come together.

30
00:02:25,370 --> 00:02:27,870
Last thing I want to warn you about is your sermon notes.

31
00:02:28,350 --> 00:02:31,710
First of all, they are for a sermon that I'm not preaching today.

32
00:02:32,190 --> 00:02:34,830
And that's nobody's fault but mine and Bruce Steele's.

33
00:02:35,010 --> 00:02:39,250
When I found out what kind of technological support that you had,

34
00:02:40,130 --> 00:02:41,490
everything spelled right?

35
00:02:41,710 --> 00:02:42,090
Yeah, okay.

36
00:02:42,290 --> 00:02:47,890
technological support you had here for the message today. I decided to do what I really

37
00:02:47,890 --> 00:02:53,290
wanted to do, and so I'm going to share with you a message entitled, One at a Time. We're in Matthew

38
00:02:53,290 --> 00:02:59,930
chapter 22, and I want to ask you a few more questions. I should have you take the scorecard

39
00:02:59,930 --> 00:03:05,350
out of the pew rack in front of you, but there isn't one there. But in your mind, take out your

40
00:03:05,350 --> 00:03:12,550
scorecard, and you can go 1 to 10, or you can go A through F, or you can do whatever you want, but

41
00:03:12,550 --> 00:03:18,750
Let's find out how you're doing. Let's take a test today. Are you walking the talk? Are you

42
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:26,640
living the way you say you believe? Are you being a wise parent? Okay, one to ten. Are you being a

43
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:35,640
faithful friend? Are you being a devoted church member? Are you an honest employee? Are you a

44
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:42,700
witness in your workplace, on your campus, in your neighborhood? Are you a caring neighbor?

45
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:45,280
Should I stop now?

46
00:03:45,940 --> 00:03:47,360
I don't like to take tests.

47
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:48,300
Do you like to take tests?

48
00:03:49,970 --> 00:03:51,230
Did you pass the test, though?

49
00:03:53,490 --> 00:03:57,030
You know, when I start taking inventory of my own life

50
00:03:57,030 --> 00:04:00,970
in this pressurized and complicated world,

51
00:04:00,970 --> 00:04:03,270
I sometimes get caught in a vice

52
00:04:03,270 --> 00:04:06,990
between the commands of a holy and perfect God

53
00:04:06,990 --> 00:04:10,640
and my own aggressive self-analysis.

54
00:04:10,820 --> 00:04:14,500
And quite frankly, life gets even more complicated then,

55
00:04:15,510 --> 00:04:16,650
and it can get painful.

56
00:04:17,590 --> 00:04:18,870
Raise your hand if you like pain.

57
00:04:20,120 --> 00:04:21,360
All right, I didn't think so.

58
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:25,560
And so what happens when we aggressively self-analyze

59
00:04:25,560 --> 00:04:27,480
and we experience that pain,

60
00:04:27,660 --> 00:04:31,240
we're inclined, frankly, to stop analyzing our lives at all.

61
00:04:31,580 --> 00:04:37,190
And we drift, and we coast, and we can stop dead.

62
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:40,540
And that's when I need to look to Jesus.

63
00:04:41,890 --> 00:04:46,520
In Matthew chapter 22, we read these words.

64
00:04:46,820 --> 00:04:49,640
Jesus has just passed the test of the Sadducees,

65
00:04:50,060 --> 00:04:53,000
And here we read,

66
00:04:53,300 --> 00:04:57,700
Hearing that Jesus had silenced the Sadducees, the Pharisees got together.

67
00:04:57,800 --> 00:04:59,360
There's always somebody who wants to test you.

68
00:05:00,270 --> 00:05:03,570
And one of them, an expert in the law, tested him with this question,

69
00:05:03,710 --> 00:05:07,300
Teacher, which is the greatest commandment in the law?

70
00:05:09,260 --> 00:05:10,500
And Jesus replied,

71
00:05:11,340 --> 00:05:15,420
Love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your mind,

72
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:18,600
excuse me, with all your soul, and with all your mind.

73
00:05:19,310 --> 00:05:22,090
This is the first and greatest commandment.

74
00:05:22,090 --> 00:05:23,990
And the second is like it.

75
00:05:24,490 --> 00:05:26,690
Love your neighbor as yourself.

76
00:05:27,190 --> 00:05:30,590
All the law and the prophets, the whole Old Testament,

77
00:05:33,460 --> 00:05:35,040
hangs on these two commandments.

78
00:05:38,780 --> 00:05:41,620
Look how simple the Savior makes life.

79
00:05:43,180 --> 00:05:43,820
Love God.

80
00:05:45,230 --> 00:05:45,890
Love your neighbor.

81
00:05:47,310 --> 00:05:47,590
Period.

82
00:05:48,210 --> 00:05:51,030
That sums up all that God wants from you.

83
00:05:51,270 --> 00:05:53,630
And yet we make life so complicated.

84
00:05:54,030 --> 00:05:56,730
We look at life as that proverbial elephant.

85
00:05:56,730 --> 00:05:58,010
And how do you eat an elephant?

86
00:05:58,010 --> 00:06:00,470
You eat an elephant one bite at a time.

87
00:06:01,210 --> 00:06:03,030
But we make life complicated.

88
00:06:03,730 --> 00:06:07,150
And if the Bible didn't make it complicated enough for us,

89
00:06:07,390 --> 00:06:09,370
because we don't read it clearly,

90
00:06:09,690 --> 00:06:11,370
we forget verses like this,

91
00:06:11,690 --> 00:06:14,010
reminders of a loving God that says simply,

92
00:06:14,130 --> 00:06:16,450
wait a second, there's a lot in here,

93
00:06:16,930 --> 00:06:18,870
and there's a lot in the world around you,

94
00:06:18,990 --> 00:06:20,870
but life is simple.

95
00:06:21,450 --> 00:06:22,930
Love God.

96
00:06:23,690 --> 00:06:25,230
Love your neighbor.

97
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:28,320
One day at a time.

98
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:31,360
One relationship at a time.

99
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:33,140
Keep it simple.

100
00:06:36,610 --> 00:06:39,570
One act of obedience at a time.

101
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,100
Walking the talk.

102
00:06:42,340 --> 00:06:44,220
One foot in front of the other.

103
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:47,100
One relationship after another.

104
00:06:47,100 --> 00:06:49,580
One decision after another.

105
00:06:50,160 --> 00:06:52,220
And that's how we get it done for God.

106
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:57,180
And that's how we experience the abundance and the joy that God wants us to have.

107
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:01,080
I want you to turn with me to John chapter 4, if you have your Bibles.

108
00:07:01,080 --> 00:07:04,140
If not, you'll get it from me and from the screen above.

109
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:11,370
It's a great passage that shows us how Jesus changed lives.

110
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:15,280
He did it one life at a time.

111
00:07:18,170 --> 00:07:19,230
Beginning with verse 1.

112
00:07:19,290 --> 00:07:23,510
The Pharisees heard that Jesus was gaining and baptizing more disciples than John,

113
00:07:23,830 --> 00:07:27,670
although in fact it was not Jesus who baptized, but his disciples.

114
00:07:28,830 --> 00:07:34,090
When the Lord learned of this, he left Judea and went back once more to Galilee.

115
00:07:34,090 --> 00:07:37,770
Now, I want to stop right there and point out one very important thing.

116
00:07:38,110 --> 00:07:40,550
God wants you to live one day at a time.

117
00:07:41,050 --> 00:07:43,070
He wants you to keep life simple.

118
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:46,150
He does not want you to live life alone.

119
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:51,700
In fact, one of the best ways to keep life simple is to have a few people in your life

120
00:07:51,700 --> 00:07:55,600
who will surround you and remind you to keep life simple

121
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:58,500
and just ask you the question, are you loving God?

122
00:07:59,000 --> 00:07:59,960
Do you love people?

123
00:08:00,440 --> 00:08:01,660
Is love your motivation?

124
00:08:01,660 --> 00:08:04,680
is God, the Lord of your life.

125
00:08:06,440 --> 00:08:07,640
Don't try to live it alone,

126
00:08:08,080 --> 00:08:09,520
or you're in for trouble.

127
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,980
Verse 4 says that Jesus had to go through Samaria

128
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:14,860
to get to Galilee.

129
00:08:14,960 --> 00:08:18,160
Well, I don't want to quibble with God's word,

130
00:08:18,300 --> 00:08:21,020
but I think John means something different

131
00:08:21,020 --> 00:08:23,580
than that Jesus had to go through Samaria,

132
00:08:23,660 --> 00:08:24,240
because you know what?

133
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:26,600
Jesus didn't have to go through Samaria.

134
00:08:26,600 --> 00:08:28,940
That was the straightest route to Galilee.

135
00:08:29,560 --> 00:08:31,380
From Jerusalem to Galilee,

136
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:32,400
you go through Samaria

137
00:08:32,400 --> 00:08:37,600
if you want to get there quickly, but the fact is that geographically it wasn't absolutely

138
00:08:37,600 --> 00:08:44,500
necessary, and culturally it was not the norm. It would be normal for Jews or Samaritans to avoid

139
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:51,400
one another at every opportunity. They had deep cultural and religious divisions, animosity

140
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:57,400
toward one another, and most Jews, if they wanted to go from Jerusalem to Galilee, would have gone

141
00:08:57,400 --> 00:08:59,640
around Samaria to get there.

142
00:09:00,790 --> 00:09:03,650
Somehow, John feels compelled to write

143
00:09:03,650 --> 00:09:05,550
that Jesus had to go through Samaria,

144
00:09:05,890 --> 00:09:08,090
and I think it's pretty simple to understand why.

145
00:09:08,710 --> 00:09:11,530
Jesus kept his route simple

146
00:09:11,530 --> 00:09:15,110
because he simply could not exclude anyone

147
00:09:15,110 --> 00:09:17,070
from the love of God.

148
00:09:17,950 --> 00:09:21,050
If God tells you to go from point A to point B,

149
00:09:21,530 --> 00:09:24,270
don't make it more complicated than it needs to be.

150
00:09:25,990 --> 00:09:26,550
Obey.

151
00:09:26,550 --> 00:09:31,190
and what he puts in your path and who he puts in your path

152
00:09:31,190 --> 00:09:32,930
will be part of his plan.

153
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,560
As Jesus moves through Samaria, we come to verse 7.

154
00:09:41,690 --> 00:09:47,200
A Samaritan woman came to the well where Jesus was to draw water.

155
00:09:47,680 --> 00:09:49,940
And Jesus said to her, Will you give me a drink?

156
00:09:50,950 --> 00:09:53,390
His disciples had gone into town to buy food.

157
00:09:53,770 --> 00:09:58,060
The Samaritan woman said to him, You are a Jew and I am a Samaritan woman.

158
00:09:58,060 --> 00:10:00,500
How can you ask me for a drink?

159
00:10:01,310 --> 00:10:04,800
For Jews do not associate with Samaritans.

160
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:06,560
Now, I'll give you a tip.

161
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:14,020
This is one of the best-known witnessing passages in the New Testament.

162
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:15,640
But I want you to notice something.

163
00:10:16,340 --> 00:10:18,980
There is nothing right about the planning here.

164
00:10:20,100 --> 00:10:23,760
Jesus obviously did not put together a flowchart on this

165
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:26,640
and how to best witness that day

166
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:30,700
because he was in the wrong place at the wrong time with the wrong woman.

167
00:10:31,660 --> 00:10:34,460
Jesus is a Jew, and this woman is a Samaritan.

168
00:10:34,540 --> 00:10:35,920
They have nothing to do with each other.

169
00:10:36,020 --> 00:10:37,920
They avoid each other like the plague.

170
00:10:38,700 --> 00:10:39,860
Jesus is a man.

171
00:10:40,320 --> 00:10:41,140
She is a woman.

172
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:45,380
Men and women did not associate in that way, that intimately.

173
00:10:48,570 --> 00:10:51,130
Jesus was the Holy Son of God.

174
00:10:52,310 --> 00:10:54,250
And she was an immoral woman.

175
00:10:54,250 --> 00:10:57,650
We know that because she's there in the heat of the day

176
00:10:57,650 --> 00:11:02,970
to draw water when all of the women of the village would have been out in the cool of the morning

177
00:11:02,970 --> 00:11:12,870
together to draw water. And as Jesus encounters this woman in the cultural context of that day,

178
00:11:12,870 --> 00:11:21,900
these people should have had nothing to do with each other. But Jesus keeps it simple. You love

179
00:11:21,900 --> 00:11:31,410
God, you love people, whoever God puts in your path. And so even to the point where Jesus allows

180
00:11:31,410 --> 00:11:39,730
himself to be served by a woman, a Samaritan woman, an immoral Samaritan woman. He actually

181
00:11:39,730 --> 00:11:50,190
humbles himself to need something from her. He asks the woman for a drink. And note that she's

182
00:11:50,190 --> 00:11:57,490
the one who objects. How can you ask me for a drink? She knows the score. She knows that she

183
00:11:57,490 --> 00:12:08,630
got all ones and no tens. And Jesus gets right to the point. Now, he begins a dialogue in which

184
00:12:08,630 --> 00:12:15,790
Jesus tells her about the gift of God that only he can give. Begins in verse 10. Jesus answered

185
00:12:15,790 --> 00:12:21,320
her, if you knew the gift of God and who it is that asks you for a drink, you would have asked

186
00:12:21,320 --> 00:12:27,340
him and he would have given you living water. Sir, the woman said, you've got nothing to draw

187
00:12:27,340 --> 00:12:33,900
with and the well is deep where can you get this living water are you greater than our father jacob

188
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:39,500
who gave us the well and drank from himself as did also his sons and his flocks and his herds and

189
00:12:39,500 --> 00:12:47,200
they go on in this dialogue this woman doesn't want to talk about the living water i'm not sure

190
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:51,120
at the beginning whether she really even understands what jesus is talking about

191
00:12:52,330 --> 00:12:56,810
She wants to talk about everything from hydrology to the history of wells.

192
00:12:57,650 --> 00:13:01,850
She wants to talk about religion and culture and ancestors.

193
00:13:02,150 --> 00:13:06,450
She wants to talk about everything but what really the subject is.

194
00:13:08,790 --> 00:13:14,450
She says to Jesus, give me water so that I won't have to come back to this well in the heat of the day anymore.

195
00:13:14,610 --> 00:13:19,690
Now, at least to some degree, she realizes now Jesus has something she doesn't have.

196
00:13:19,690 --> 00:13:23,290
I'm still not sure she fully grasps what's going on.

197
00:13:23,570 --> 00:13:25,530
And Jesus responds to her,

198
00:13:26,310 --> 00:13:28,290
go get your husband and bring him back.

199
00:13:30,060 --> 00:13:32,720
Now, that seems to me like he changed the subject.

200
00:13:33,520 --> 00:13:33,720
Okay?

201
00:13:34,040 --> 00:13:36,940
This is what my wife says I do to her when we're talking.

202
00:13:37,540 --> 00:13:38,760
Don't change the subject.

203
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:40,040
I don't think I did.

204
00:13:41,010 --> 00:13:42,450
Well, he didn't change the subject.

205
00:13:42,550 --> 00:13:44,390
She just didn't know what the subject was.

206
00:13:45,190 --> 00:13:46,390
And at that point,

207
00:13:46,710 --> 00:13:48,730
Jesus is going to get down to the point

208
00:13:48,730 --> 00:13:53,210
at which she has to deal with the obstacle, or at least one of the obstacles,

209
00:13:53,790 --> 00:13:58,990
that has kept her from ever receiving the eternally satisfying love of God.

210
00:14:01,160 --> 00:14:04,100
But I want you to note something else that's important for us.

211
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:10,180
He is also giving her the opportunity to sneak away into town and not come back.

212
00:14:11,540 --> 00:14:15,960
That doesn't seem like a profound theological statement, but I think it's pretty important.

213
00:14:17,450 --> 00:14:20,210
Jesus was not depending on his pressure

214
00:14:20,210 --> 00:14:24,670
and keeping her there, buttonholed, pigeonholed,

215
00:14:24,810 --> 00:14:26,760
to respond to his offer.

216
00:14:28,900 --> 00:14:32,340
In order to put his finger on the point,

217
00:14:32,480 --> 00:14:35,340
on the obstacle that's keeping her from God's love,

218
00:14:35,680 --> 00:14:37,700
he is willing to let her get away.

219
00:14:40,830 --> 00:14:43,610
Sometimes people come under extreme conviction

220
00:14:43,610 --> 00:14:46,590
before they get right with God.

221
00:14:48,760 --> 00:14:51,820
And God uses all kinds of ways to wake people up.

222
00:14:52,280 --> 00:14:58,610
It can be a soft whisper, the serenity of creation, of nature.

223
00:15:00,610 --> 00:15:04,630
Or it can be the exposure of life-threatening circumstances.

224
00:15:04,630 --> 00:15:09,970
It can be just a subtle sense of thirst, or it can be a near drowning.

225
00:15:11,620 --> 00:15:16,660
But nobody ever came to Christ because another person forced them.

226
00:15:17,780 --> 00:15:19,880
And so Jesus keeps it simple.

227
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:23,540
It's up to her to open her heart to God

228
00:15:23,540 --> 00:15:27,900
if she's going to experience the love of God.

229
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,540
Now, if we approached our witness,

230
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:34,900
our sharing of the love of God that way,

231
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,740
wouldn't that just take some tension

232
00:15:36,740 --> 00:15:39,020
out of the fear we have of witnessing?

233
00:15:40,210 --> 00:15:41,330
Now, if you're normal,

234
00:15:42,340 --> 00:15:43,960
it's okay to be normal

235
00:15:43,960 --> 00:15:46,460
and feel afraid about witnessing,

236
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:47,740
because let's be honest, we do.

237
00:15:48,360 --> 00:15:49,820
We fear rejection.

238
00:15:50,900 --> 00:15:52,460
We fear humiliation.

239
